{
  "texts": [
    "One of the key points Foucault makes is that the author is not merely an individual who creates a text, but rather a complex function that is constructed by the text itself and by the norms and expectations of the society in which it circulates (1969).",
    "The Enlightenment period significantly advanced the concept of individual authorship in scientific discourse.",
    "This era emphasized reason, empirical evidence, and the systematic pursuit of knowledge, leading to the rise of the 'scientist' as a distinct professional identity (Porter 1990).",
    "Notable figures such as Isaac Newton and Robert Boyle epitomized the individual scientist whose work, discoveries, and publications were attributed directly to them, reflecting their personal intellectual endeavors (Shapin 1995).",
    "This shift was supported by the establishment of scientific societies and journals, which provided platforms for individual scientists to disseminate their work and claim intellectual ownership (Kronick 1976)."
  ]
}